-----------------------------------------------------------
CVE-2019-18277: HTTP Request Smuggling (CL.TE Desync)
-----------------------------------------------------------
CVE ID: CVE-2019-18277
CVSS Score: Not retrieved due to Cloudflare blocking
Severity: IMPORTANT (based on HAProxy advisory)
Published: October 23, 2019
Last Modified: November 20, 2024

AFFECTED VERSIONS:
- HAProxy before 2.0.6 (specifically includes version 2.0.5)
- cpe:2.3:a:haproxy:haproxy:*:*:*:*:*:*:*:* (versions up to excluding 2.0.6)

TECHNICAL DESCRIPTION:
A flaw was found in HAProxy before 2.0.6 operating in legacy mode. Messages 
featuring a Transfer-Encoding header missing the "chunked" value were not 
being correctly rejected according to HTTP specification compliance.

The vulnerability manifests when:
1. HAProxy runs in legacy mode
2. A malformed Transfer-Encoding header is present (without "chunked" value)
3. Combined with "http-reuse always" setting enabled

ATTACK VECTOR:
HTTP Request Smuggling - CL.TE variant (Content-Length vs Transfer-Encoding)

EXPLOITATION CONDITIONS:
- Target must be running HAProxy 2.0.5 or earlier
- Legacy mode must be enabled
- "http-reuse always" setting must be configured
- Backend must employ a lenient parser that ignores Content-Length after 
  seeing Transfer-Encoding header (even if malformed)

IMPACT:
- HTTP Request Smuggling attacks
- Bypass of security controls and filters
- Cache poisoning
- Credential and session hijacking
- Potential for backend request manipulation

VULNERABILITY MECHANISM:
The flaw allows malicious actors to craft requests where:
- Transfer-Encoding header is present but malformed (missing "chunked")
- Content-Length header is also present
- HAProxy's ambiguous parsing creates request interpretation differences
- Results in request boundaries being misinterpreted by backend servers

WORKAROUNDS:
- Do not use "http-reuse always" setting in legacy mode
- Upgrade to HAProxy 2.0.6 or later
- Implement strict HTTP parsing validation in backend applications

MITIGATION:
Upgrade to HAProxy 2.0.6 or later version

REFERENCES:
- NVD: https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2019-18277
- CVE: https://cve.mitre.org/cgi-bin/cvename.cgi?name=CVE-2019-18277
- HAProxy Security Advisories: https://www.haproxy.org/security.html

-----------------------------------------------------------
CVE-2020-11100: HTTP/2 HPACK Buffer Overflow
-----------------------------------------------------------
CVE ID: CVE-2020-11100
CVSS Score: Not retrieved due to Cloudflare blocking
Severity: CRITICAL
Published: April 2, 2020
Last Modified: November 20, 2024

AFFECTED VERSIONS:
- HAProxy 1.8.0 through 2.x before 2.1.4
- Specifically includes HAProxy 2.0.5
- cpe:2.3:a:haproxy:haproxy:*:*:*:*:*:*:*:* (versions 1.8.0 up to excluding 2.1.4)

TECHNICAL DESCRIPTION:
In hpack_dht_insert function in hpack-tbl.c in the HPACK decoder component,
a remote attacker can write arbitrary bytes around a specific location on 
the heap via a carefully crafted HTTP/2 request.

ROOT CAUSE:
Buffer overflow vulnerability in HTTP/2 HPACK decoder dynamic table insertion
- Insufficient bounds checking in hpack_dht_insert()
- Heap-based buffer overflow allows out-of-bounds memory writes
- Results from malformed HPACK-encoded headers in HTTP/2 frames

ATTACK VECTOR:
- Network-based attack via HTTP/2 protocol
- Requires ability to send crafted HTTP/2 requests to vulnerable HAProxy
- No authentication required for exploitation

EXPLOITATION CONDITIONS:
- HAProxy must be accepting HTTP/2 connections
- Attacker must be able to send HTTP/2 requests
- Crafted HPACK-encoded headers trigger the overflow

IMPACT:
- Arbitrary memory write (heap corruption)
- Remote Code Execution (RCE) - HIGHLY CRITICAL
- Potential complete system compromise
- Denial of Service through memory corruption
- Information disclosure through heap manipulation

VULNERABILITY SPECIFICS:
The vulnerability occurs in the HPACK (Header Compression for HTTP/2) decoder
when processing dynamic table insertions:
- Malformed HPACK data triggers buffer overflow
- Allows writing controlled data to adjacent heap memory regions
- Can corrupt data structures, function pointers, or metadata
- May lead to arbitrary code execution depending on heap layout

ATTACK SCENARIOS:
1. RCE Attack: Craft HTTP/2 request with malformed HPACK to overwrite function 
   pointers or control structures
2. DoS Attack: Corrupt heap metadata to cause immediate crash
3. Info Leak: Manipulate heap to expose sensitive data

AFFECTED PLATFORMS (from CPE data):
- Debian Linux 10.0, 18.04 LTS, 19.10
- Fedora 30, 31
- openSUSE Leap 15.1
- Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform 3.11, 4.0
- Ubuntu Linux 18.04 LTS, 19.10

MITIGATION:
IMMEDIATE: Upgrade to HAProxy 2.1.4 or later
WORKAROUND: Disable HTTP/2 support if not required

REFERENCES:
- NVD: https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2020-11100
- CVE: https://cve.mitre.org/cgi-bin/cvename.cgi?name=CVE-2020-11100
- HAProxy Security Advisories: https://www.haproxy.org/security.html

-------------------------------------------
